          "context": "The Java Memory Model (JMM) defines how threads interact through memory and what values a thread may see for a shared variable. The happens-before relationship guarantees that writes in one thread are visible to reads in another thread that observes the ordering. Volatile variables establish a happens-before edge: a write to a volatile variable happens-before any subsequent read of that variable. Synchronization (entering a monitor) happens-before the matching monitorexit; all writes before the lock release are visible after lock acquisition. The JMM allows reordering of instructions by the compiler and CPU as long as the happens-before ordering is not violated for the executing thread. The double-checked locking idiom for Singleton requires the instance field to be volatile to work correctly under the JMM. Thread.start() happens-before any action in the started thread; Thread.join() completes after all actions in the joined thread. Final fields are guaranteed to be visible to all threads once the constructor completes, without synchronization. Out-of-thin-air values are values that appear as if from nowhere due to speculative execution; the JMM prohibits them. Publication safety requires an object to be safely published (via volatile, final, or synchronization) before sharing it with other threads.",
