        {
          "context": "Virtual threads (Project Loom, Java 21) are lightweight threads managed by the JVM, not the OS. Platform threads (traditional) map 1:1 to OS threads \u2014 expensive, limited to thousands. Virtual threads are multiplexed onto a small pool of carrier (platform) threads. Creating a virtual thread: Thread.ofVirtual().start(runnable). ExecutorService e = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor() creates one virtual thread per task. Virtual threads block cheaply \u2014 when a virtual thread blocks on I/O, the carrier thread is freed. Virtual threads simplify the 'one-thread-per-request' model for high-throughput servers.",
