    {
      "title": "GC Tuning",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "Java provides several garbage collectors: Serial GC, Parallel GC, G1 GC (default since Java 9), ZGC (low latency), and Shenandoah GC. Each is selected via JVM flags: -XX:+UseG1GC, -XX:+UseZGC, -XX:+UseShenandoahGC. Each has different throughput and latency trade-offs suitable for different workloads.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1034",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "Which garbage collector is the default since Java 9?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "G1 GC",
                  "answer_start": 66
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "The JVM heap is divided into Young Generation (Eden plus two Survivor spaces) and Old Generation. New objects are allocated in Eden. Minor GC collects Young Generation; Major or Full GC collects Old Generation. The metaspace stores class metadata and is not part of the heap.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1035",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "Where are new objects allocated in the JVM heap?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Eden",
                  "answer_start": 47
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "G1 GC divides the heap into equal-sized regions. Instead of fixed Young/Old areas, regions are dynamically assigned. G1 collects regions with the most garbage first (Garbage First). It targets a pause time goal set with -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis. G1 performs concurrent marking to identify live objects without stopping all application threads.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1036",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What does the -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis flag control in G1 GC?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "the target pause time goal for G1 GC",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "ZGC is a low-latency garbage collector that performs most work concurrently with application threads. ZGC uses colored pointers and load barriers to track object references during concurrent collection. Its pause times are typically sub-millisecond regardless of heap size, making it suitable for latency-sensitive applications.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1037",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What technique does ZGC use to track object references during concurrent collection?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "colored pointers and load barriers",
                  "answer_start": 111
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Memory leaks in Java occur when objects are still referenced but no longer needed. Common causes: static collections holding references, event listeners not deregistered, inner class holding outer class reference, ThreadLocal variables not removed. Tools to diagnose: heap dumps analyzed with Eclipse MAT or VisualVM, jmap -dump:live to capture live heap dump.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1038",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "What are common causes of memory leaks in Java?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "static collections, underegistered event listeners, inner class references, ThreadLocal not removed",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Choosing between G1 and ZGC: G1 offers good throughput with controllable pause times (default 200ms goal). ZGC offers near-zero pauses but slightly lower throughput due to concurrent overhead. For batch processing or analytics, G1 or Parallel GC maximizes throughput. For web APIs or real-time systems, ZGC reduces latency outliers.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1039",
              "bt_level": "BT5",
              "question": "When would you choose ZGC over G1 GC?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "When near-zero pause times are required, such as in trading engines or real-time systems",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "GC pressure occurs when short-lived objects are created at a high rate, causing frequent minor GCs. Strategies to reduce GC pressure: object pooling to reuse expensive objects, flyweight pattern, avoid String concatenation in loops (use StringBuilder), reduce autoboxing by using primitive collections.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1040",
              "bt_level": "BT6",
              "question": "What strategies would you implement to reduce GC pressure in a high-throughput Java service?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Object pooling, avoiding autoboxing, using StringBuilder, flyweight pattern, and primitive collections",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "JVM Flags",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "JVM flags fall into three categories: standard flags, non-standard flags (-X flags like -Xmx and -Xms), and advanced flags (-XX flags). Advanced flags use boolean syntax: -XX:+FlagName to enable and -XX:-FlagName to disable. Diagnostic flags require -XX:+UnlockDiagnosticVMOptions first.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1041",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What syntax enables an advanced JVM boolean flag?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "-XX:+FlagName",
                  "answer_start": 171
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "The -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal flag prints all JVM flags and their current values at startup. This is useful for verifying that ergonomics (automatic tuning by the JVM based on available hardware) has set appropriate defaults. -XX:+PrintCommandLineFlags shows only flags explicitly set or modified by ergonomics.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1042",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "Which JVM flag prints all current JVM flag values at startup?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "-XX:+PrintFlagsFinal",
                  "answer_start": 4
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "JVM ergonomics automatically configures heap size, GC algorithm, and other settings based on machine resources. In containerized environments, ergonomics may read host memory instead of container limits. Using -XX:+UseContainerSupport (default on since Java 10) fixes this so the JVM correctly reads container memory limits.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1043",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What problem does -XX:+UseContainerSupport solve?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "It ensures JVM ergonomics reads container memory limits instead of host memory",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "To auto-capture a heap dump on OutOfMemoryError, use the JVM flag -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError. The dump can also be triggered programmatically via the HotSpot Diagnostic MBean: ManagementFactory.getPlatformMXBean(HotSpotDiagnosticMXBean.class).dumpHeap(filename, true). Heap dumps are analyzed with tools like Eclipse MAT or VisualVM.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1044",
              "bt_level": "BT3",
              "question": "Which JVM flag automatically captures a heap dump when an OutOfMemoryError occurs?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "-XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError",
                  "answer_start": 66
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "JIT compilation flags: -XX:+TieredCompilation (default) uses C1 for fast compile then C2 for optimizing compile. -XX:CompileThreshold sets invocation count before JIT. Deoptimization happens when speculative optimizations are invalidated, for example when an interface gets a new implementation. -XX:+TraceDeoptimization shows deopt events.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1045",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "What is deoptimization in the JVM context?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "When speculative optimizations are invalidated and the JVM reverts to interpreted execution",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Safepoints are moments when all JVM threads are stopped for GC or other operations. -XX:+PrintSafepointStatistics shows safepoint frequency and time. High time-to-safepoint indicates threads are slow to reach a safepoint. Long counted loops can delay safepoints; use -XX:+UseCountedLoopSafepoints to add checks inside loops.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1046",
              "bt_level": "BT5",
              "question": "What causes high time-to-safepoint and how can it be resolved?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Long counted loops delaying safepoint checks; use -XX:+UseCountedLoopSafepoints",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Jakarta EE",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE) is a set of specifications for enterprise Java development. Key APIs include: Servlet, JSP, JSF for UI, CDI for dependency injection, JPA for persistence, EJB for business components, JAX-RS for REST, JAX-WS for SOAP, JMS for messaging, and Bean Validation. Implementations include WildFly, GlassFish, Payara, and Open Liberty.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1076",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What does CDI stand for in Jakarta EE?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Contexts and Dependency Injection",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "CDI provides bean management and dependency injection. Beans are injected with @Inject. Scopes include @RequestScoped for per HTTP request, @SessionScoped for per HTTP session, @ApplicationScoped for singleton per deployment, and @Dependent for scope of injecting bean. @Named makes beans accessible from EL expressions.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1077",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "Which CDI scope creates one bean instance per HTTP session?",
              "answers": [
