                  "text": "@SessionScoped",
                  "answer_start": 140
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "JAX-RS annotations: @Path defines URI path, @GET, @POST, @PUT, and @DELETE map HTTP methods, @Produces and @Consumes set media types, @PathParam, @QueryParam, and @HeaderParam bind parameters. @ApplicationPath sets the base URI. Implementations include Jersey, RESTEasy, and Apache CXF.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1078",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What JAX-RS annotation defines the base URI for a REST application?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "@ApplicationPath",
                  "answer_start": 193
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Bean Validation provides annotation-based validation: @NotNull, @NotBlank, @Size(min, max), @Min, @Max, @Email, @Pattern for regex, @Past, @Future. Validation is triggered automatically in JAX-RS and JSF. @Valid cascades validation to nested objects. Custom validators implement ConstraintValidator.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1079",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "Which Bean Validation annotation validates that a field matches a regular expression?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "@Pattern",
                  "answer_start": 112
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "EJB types: Stateless Session Bean annotated @Stateless has no conversational state and is pooled, Stateful Session Bean annotated @Stateful maintains client state, Singleton Bean annotated @Singleton has one instance per JVM. EJBs provide container-managed transactions, security, concurrency, and remoting capabilities.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1080",
              "bt_level": "BT3",
              "question": "Which EJB type maintains conversational state with the client?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Stateful Session Bean (@Stateful)",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "JMS supports two messaging models: Point-to-Point using Queue where one consumer receives each message, and Publish-Subscribe using Topic where multiple subscribers receive each message. Message-Driven Beans annotated @MessageDriven listen to JMS queues or topics asynchronously. JMS providers include ActiveMQ and IBM MQ.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1081",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "What is the difference between JMS Queue and Topic messaging models?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Queue delivers each message to one consumer; Topic delivers each message to all subscribers",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE) is the enterprise edition specification for building large-scale Java applications. It is governed by the Eclipse Foundation since 2019 after Oracle transferred the javax namespace to jakarta. Key specifications include Jakarta Servlet, Jakarta Persistence (JPA), Jakarta RESTful Web Services (JAX-RS), Jakarta Messaging (JMS), and Jakarta Contexts and Dependency Injection (CDI). Application servers implementing Jakarta EE include WildFly, Payara, Open Liberty, and GlassFish. CDI beans use @Inject for dependency injection and can have scopes such as @RequestScoped, @SessionScoped, and @ApplicationScoped. JAX-RS enables REST APIs using annotations like @GET, @POST, @Path, and @Produces. JPA maps Java objects to relational database tables using @Entity, @Table, @Id, and @Column. Jakarta EE 10 requires Java SE 11 or later and dropped deprecated APIs such as javax.xml.bind. MicroProfile is a complementary set of specifications tailored for microservices built on Jakarta EE. Jakarta EE profiles \u2014 Web Profile and Core Profile \u2014 allow lighter runtimes by including only necessary specifications.",
