    {
      "title": "GraphQL Java",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "GraphQL is a query language for APIs where clients specify exactly what data they need. Unlike REST which returns fixed response shapes, GraphQL returns only requested fields. Java implementations include graphql-java (core), Spring for GraphQL (Spring Boot integration), and Netflix DGS Framework. Schema is defined in SDL (Schema Definition Language) files.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1082",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What is the main advantage of GraphQL over REST regarding data fetching?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Clients specify exactly what data they need, receiving only requested fields",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "GraphQL operations: Query for reading data, Mutation for writing or modifying data, and Subscription for real-time updates over WebSocket. Types include scalar (Int, Float, String, Boolean, ID), object, enum, input, interface, and union. The schema is the contract between client and server.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1083",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "Which GraphQL operation type is used for real-time updates?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Subscription",
                  "answer_start": 88
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "In Spring for GraphQL, @QueryMapping maps a GraphQL query to a method, @MutationMapping handles mutations, @SubscriptionMapping handles subscriptions, and @SchemaMapping resolves specific fields. @Argument binds GraphQL arguments to method parameters. DataFetcher is the core graphql-java abstraction for resolving fields.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1084",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "Which annotation in Spring for GraphQL maps a method to a GraphQL query?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "@QueryMapping",
                  "answer_start": 23
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "The N+1 problem in GraphQL: fetching a list of entities each with nested fields may invoke the field resolver N times (once per entity). Solution: DataLoader (BatchLoader) batches multiple keys and fetches them in a single database call. Spring for GraphQL supports @BatchMapping for automatic batching of nested field resolvers.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1085",
              "bt_level": "BT3",
              "question": "How does DataLoader solve the N+1 problem in GraphQL?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "DataLoader batches multiple keys and fetches them in a single database call",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "GraphQL security considerations: depth limiting prevents deeply nested malicious queries, query complexity analysis assigns cost to each field and rejects queries exceeding a threshold, query whitelisting only allows pre-approved queries in production, field-level authorization uses @PreAuthorize or custom directives, and introspection should be disabled in production.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1086",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "What techniques protect a GraphQL API from malicious deeply nested queries?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Depth limiting and query complexity analysis",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "gRPC Java",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "gRPC is a high-performance RPC framework using Protocol Buffers for serialization and HTTP/2 for transport. In Java, the grpc-java library provides the implementation. Services are defined in .proto files; the protoc compiler generates Java stubs. gRPC supports four communication patterns: unary, server streaming, client streaming, and bidirectional streaming.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1087",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What serialization format does gRPC use?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Protocol Buffers (protobuf)",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Protocol Buffers field numbers identify fields in binary encoding and must not change after deployment. The repeated keyword in a message definition denotes a list field. The oneof keyword allows at most one field in a group to be set. Message definitions go in .proto files and are compiled to Java classes with protoc.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1088",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What is the purpose of field numbers in Protocol Buffers?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Field numbers identify fields in binary encoding and must not change after deployment",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "gRPC service types: Unary sends a single request and receives a single response similar to HTTP REST. Server Streaming sends a single request and receives a stream of responses. Client Streaming sends a stream of requests and receives a single response. Bidirectional Streaming has both sides streaming concurrently. Streaming is defined with the stream keyword in the .proto service definition.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1089",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "How is server streaming defined in a gRPC .proto service?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Using the stream keyword before the response type in the service method definition",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "gRPC interceptors implement ClientInterceptor or ServerInterceptor. Common uses: authentication via metadata token checking, logging, tracing, and retry logic. gRPC metadata is the equivalent of HTTP headers and uses the Metadata class to pass key-value pairs with requests.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1090",
              "bt_level": "BT3",
              "question": "What is the gRPC equivalent of HTTP headers?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Metadata",
                  "answer_start": 221
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "gRPC uses HTTP/2 with multiplexing and header compression, while REST typically uses HTTP/1.1. Protobuf serialization is 3-10x smaller and faster than JSON. gRPC enforces a strict schema while REST with JSON is schema-optional. gRPC is better for internal microservice communication; REST is better for public APIs and browser clients.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1091",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "Why is gRPC better suited for internal microservice communication than REST?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "gRPC uses HTTP/2, binary protobuf serialization that is faster and smaller, and enforces strict schema",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "gRPC load balancing strategies: client-side where stubs resolve multiple endpoints and load balance locally, look-aside where an external resolver like Consul handles it, and service mesh where Istio or Linkerd handle routing transparently. For Kubernetes, headless services return all pod IPs enabling client-side load balancing.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1092",
              "bt_level": "BT5",
              "question": "What is the advantage of client-side gRPC load balancing in Kubernetes?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Headless services return all pod IPs, enabling per-request load balancing rather than per-connection",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Microservices Patterns",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "The Circuit Breaker pattern prevents cascading failures in microservices. States: Closed where requests flow normally, Open where requests fail fast without calling the service, and Half-Open where trial requests test recovery. Implemented in Spring Boot with Resilience4j using @CircuitBreaker annotation.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1103",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What are the three states of a Circuit Breaker?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Closed, Open, and Half-Open",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Service discovery allows microservices to find each other without hardcoded addresses. Client-side discovery: the service queries a registry like Eureka and load balances locally. Server-side discovery: the load balancer queries the registry on behalf of the client. Spring Cloud Netflix Eureka implements client-side discovery.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1104",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What is the difference between client-side and server-side service discovery?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Client-side queries the registry locally; server-side has the load balancer query the registry",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "The Saga pattern manages distributed transactions across microservices. Choreography has services publish events that others react to. Orchestration uses a central saga orchestrator that sends commands to services. Compensating transactions undo completed steps on failure. Sagas provide eventual consistency without distributed ACID transactions.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1105",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What are the two Saga implementation styles?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Choreography (event-driven) and Orchestration (central orchestrator)",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "API Gateway patterns include authentication and authorization, SSL termination, request routing, rate limiting, request aggregation which combines multiple service calls into one response, and protocol translation. Spring Cloud Gateway uses reactive WebFlux for implementation.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1106",
              "bt_level": "BT2",
              "question": "What is request aggregation in an API Gateway?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Combining multiple backend service calls into a single response for the client",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Event sourcing stores state changes as a sequence of immutable events rather than current state. Replaying events reconstructs current state. Benefits include full audit trail, temporal queries, and event replay for debugging. CQRS separates the write model producing events from the read model optimized for queries. Axon Framework implements both patterns in Java.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1107",
              "bt_level": "BT3",
              "question": "What is the benefit of storing state as events in Event Sourcing?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Full audit trail, temporal queries, and the ability to replay events for debugging",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Distributed tracing tracks requests across microservices. Each request gets a trace ID and each service call gets a span ID. Trace context propagates via HTTP headers using B3 headers or W3C TraceContext format. Tools include Zipkin and Jaeger. Spring Boot integrates via Micrometer Tracing. Sampling rate controls trace volume.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1108",
              "bt_level": "BT4",
              "question": "How is trace context propagated between microservices?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Via HTTP headers using B3 headers or W3C TraceContext format",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "The Outbox pattern solves the dual-write problem where a service must write to its database and publish an event atomically. Write to an outbox table in the same database transaction as the domain change. A separate publisher reads the outbox and publishes events to Kafka, then marks records as published. Debezium CDC can automate outbox publication.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1109",
              "bt_level": "BT5",
              "question": "What problem does the Outbox pattern solve and how?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "Dual-write inconsistency; write to DB and outbox table atomically, then publish from outbox separately",
                  "answer_start": 0
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "context": "Microservices decomposition using Domain-Driven Design: bounded contexts define service boundaries, each service owns its database (database-per-service pattern), decompose by business capability or subdomain. Avoid distributed monoliths where services deploy together or share databases. Use the Strangler Fig pattern to incrementally migrate a monolith to microservices.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1110",
              "bt_level": "BT6",
              "question": "Design a decomposition strategy for migrating a monolith to microservices.",
