      "title": "Java Memory Leaks",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "A memory leak in Java occurs when objects are no longer needed but are still referenced, preventing garbage collection. Static fields holding large collections are a common source of leaks because they live for the application's lifetime. Inner classes implicitly hold a reference to their enclosing class instance, which can prevent the outer object from being collected. Unclosed resources like streams, connections, or files keep native memory allocated even if the Java heap object is collected. Caches that grow unboundedly without eviction policies cause gradual heap exhaustion. ThreadLocal variables must be removed explicitly; otherwise they can retain objects as long as the thread lives. Tools for detecting leaks include Java Flight Recorder, Eclipse MAT (Memory Analyzer Tool), and VisualVM. Weak references (WeakReference, SoftReference) allow the GC to collect objects when memory is scarce. The -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError JVM flag captures a heap dump automatically on OOME for post-mortem analysis. Event listeners registered on long-lived objects and never deregistered are another common leak source.",
