          "context": "Java object serialization converts an object graph into a byte stream for storage or transmission via ObjectOutputStream. A class must implement java.io.Serializable (a marker interface) to be serializable. The serialVersionUID field is a class-level version identifier; if it is not declared, the JVM generates one automatically based on the class structure. Transient fields are excluded from serialization and initialized to their default values upon deserialization. Deserialization restores the object graph using ObjectInputStream without calling any constructor. The readObject() and writeObject() private methods allow customizing serialization logic within a class. Externalizable extends Serializable and requires implementing readExternal() and writeExternal() for complete control over serialization. Java serialization is a known security risk; deserializing untrusted data can lead to remote code execution (gadget chain attacks). ObjectInputFilter (Java 9+) allows filtering incoming serialization data to mitigate deserialization attacks. Modern alternatives to Java serialization include JSON (Jackson/Gson), Protocol Buffers, and Kryo for safer or more efficient serialization.",
