          "context": "The Producer-Consumer pattern decouples producers of data from consumers using a shared blocking queue. BlockingQueue implementations like ArrayBlockingQueue (bounded) and LinkedBlockingQueue (optionally bounded) handle synchronization automatically. The Read-Write Lock pattern allows multiple concurrent readers but exclusive writer access, implemented via ReentrantReadWriteLock. StampedLock (Java 8+) improves on ReadWriteLock by providing an optimistic read mode that does not block writers. The Active Object pattern encapsulates a method request and its execution in separate threads using a request queue and a scheduler thread. The Monitor Object pattern synchronizes concurrent method execution within an object using condition variables. The Half-Sync/Half-Async pattern separates synchronous and asynchronous processing layers with a queue between them. The Thread-Per-Message pattern creates a new thread for each incoming request and is simplified by virtual threads in Java 21. CompletableFuture implements the Promise pattern, allowing chaining of asynchronous tasks with thenApply(), thenCompose(), and exceptionally(). The Reactor pattern uses an event loop (single thread) to dispatch I/O events to handlers, forming the basis of frameworks like Netty.",
