      "title": "Java Thread Communication",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "context": "Java provides multiple mechanisms for inter-thread communication and coordination beyond basic synchronization. Object.wait() causes the current thread to wait until another thread calls notify() or notifyAll() on the same object. notify() wakes up one arbitrary waiting thread; notifyAll() wakes all waiting threads, which then compete for the lock. wait() must be called inside a synchronized block; spurious wakeups require rechecking the condition in a loop. Condition objects from ReentrantLock provide await(), signal(), and signalAll() as more flexible alternatives to wait/notify. The producer-consumer pattern with Condition: producers call await() when the buffer is full; consumers call signal() after consuming. LockSupport.park() and LockSupport.unpark(thread) are lower-level primitives used internally by AQS-based synchronizers. AbstractQueuedSynchronizer (AQS) is the framework underlying ReentrantLock, Semaphore, CountDownLatch, and other synchronizers. Thread.interrupt() sets the interrupted flag; blocking methods like sleep() and wait() throw InterruptedException when interrupted. Thread.isInterrupted() checks the flag without clearing it; Thread.interrupted() checks and clears the interrupted flag.",
          "qas": [
            {
              "id": "java_1898",
              "bt_level": "BT1",
              "question": "What method wakes all threads waiting on an object's monitor?",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "notifyAll()",
                  "answer_start": 199
                }
              ]
            },
            {
