        {
          "context": "HashMap in Java uses an array of buckets where each bucket holds entries that share the same hash-code bucket index. The default initial capacity is 16; once the number of entries exceeds capacity multiplied by the load factor of 0.75, rehashing occurs. During rehashing the bucket array is doubled in size and all existing entries are redistributed. Java 8 introduced treeification: when a single bucket chain exceeds eight entries it becomes a red-black tree (TREEIFY_THRESHOLD=8). ConcurrentHashMap replaces the single lock of Hashtable with segment-level or node-level fine-grained locking for better throughput. LinkedHashMap maintains a doubly-linked list of entries in insertion order and can be used as an LRU cache by overriding removeEldestEntry. TreeMap keeps keys sorted by natural ordering or a supplied Comparator, with O(log n) complexity for get, put, and remove. HashMap permits one null key placed in bucket zero, and permits any number of null values. IdentityHashMap uses System.identityHashCode and reference equality instead of hashCode/equals, useful for graph traversal. The hashCode contract states that objects considered equal by equals must return identical hash codes.",
